# Keep the oh-shit moment. Cut the machinery.

<p class="lead">Run 06 produced a genuinely useful issue-progress loop. The one-hour version should be an on-rails replay of that build: tour the prepared rig, grill the vision, set up the repo baseline, make the reliability floor, project it through Lakebed, control it from Pi and Herdr, then climb toward safe dispatch, bounded maintenance, specialists, and supervisor runtime shadowing.</p>

<StatLine items={stats} />

<FeedbackParagraph id="premise" storagePrefix={feedbackStoragePrefix} note="Source: curated run-06 transcript and artifact analysis, not raw transcript publication.">
  <p>The promise is not “start from nothing in an hour.” The promise is “feel the important moves from run 06 without losing the hour to install/auth/debug sludge.” Lessons are the rails, not issue tickets. Issues are the product substrate the learner builds toward. By the end, the loop should be starting to use its own issue surface to progress work.</p>
</FeedbackParagraph>

<PatternCards items={patterns} storagePrefix={feedbackStoragePrefix} />

## The workshop is the state machine

<FeedbackParagraph id="lesson-machine" storagePrefix={feedbackStoragePrefix} note="This reframes the hour from a feature build into a sequence of teachable loop states.">
  <p>The lesson is not “generate an issue tracker from scratch.” The lesson is to rebuild the run-06 example as a trustworthy state machine: events enter, guards decide, actions write receipts, and Lakebed projects the current state. The start state should already be interesting; the hour teaches why each piece exists and how the loop becomes reliable.</p>
</FeedbackParagraph>

<div class="table-wrap lesson-state-table">
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Workshop state</th><th>Topic to teach</th><th>Proof in the demo</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      {#each lessonStates as lesson}
        <tr><td>{lesson.state}</td><td>{lesson.teaches}</td><td>{lesson.proof}</td></tr>
      {/each}
    </tbody>
  </table>
</div>

## Test pass: rebuild the machine

<FeedbackParagraph id="lesson-pass" storagePrefix={feedbackStoragePrefix} note="Use this as the next working pass: Joel can run through the lessons, write notes per lesson, then export feedback.">
  <p>This is the playable worksheet version. Work through it as the learner testing the hour: each lesson gives a challenge, starter prompt, build/operate target, evidence to inspect, discussion point, checkpoint, tiny drill, and run-06 scar. Lesson 01 is an active tour plus <code>grill-with-docs</code> vision/repo setup. The lessons are rails; the issue queue is the product substrate the learner builds toward.</p>
</FeedbackParagraph>

<div class="state-boundaries">
  <section>
    <h3>Starting state</h3>
    <p>A useful repo and workshop computer are already alive: normal Pi, two Herdr panes, source mirrors, Matt Pocock skills, Lakebed shell, scaffold daemon, and a tiny Pi helper extension.</p>
  </section>
  <section>
    <h3>End state</h3>
    <p>The repo has a captured vision, issue-event surface, typed loop check, Lakebed projection, Pi/Herdr controls, and starts progressing or maintaining work with receipts.</p>
  </section>
</div>

<LessonPass lessons={lessonPass} storagePrefix={feedbackStoragePrefix} />

<span id="what-the-logs-say"></span>

## What the run logs say

<FeedbackParagraph id="what-the-logs-say" storagePrefix={feedbackStoragePrefix} note="These are curated findings from run 06. Keep the raw Pi JSONL local.">
  <p>The app became useful when Joel stopped treating it as a side UI and started using it as the operator surface. The recurring friction was not “we need more features.” It was: the bridge is offline, the loop is sitting there, the board is hard to read, ready work is not picked up, open pre-approved work is stale, dirty loop artifacts stop the gardener, and work that still needs grilling must not auto-run.</p>
</FeedbackParagraph>

<div class="table-wrap">
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Observed friction</th><th>What it taught</th><th>Hour-cut response</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Board hard to read</td><td>The operator needs compact lanes and live state, not a data dump.</td><td>Preseed a tiny Lakebed kanban/list board.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Bridge offline / stale</td><td>Daemon health must be visible beside issue state.</td><td>Run a tiny loop pane and show status/control events.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Ready work not picked up</td><td>The loop needs an explicit decision point and receipt.</td><td>Build one check that projects events and writes evidence.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Open pre-approved backlog</td><td>Promotion is a decision, not a random script.</td><td>Show exactly one progression event after the check.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Over-eager automation</td><td>Input-required work must stay blocked until grilled.</td><td>Keep one visible approval/input gate in the UI.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
</div>

## Where the hour starts

<FeedbackParagraph id="start-state" storagePrefix={feedbackStoragePrefix} note="This is the recommended scaffold boundary, not the product outcome.">
  <p>Start with a useful repo, not a fake blank slate. The workshop computer, remote Herdr session, normal Pi, guardrails, Lakebed shell, loop pane, and basic extension/control surface should already exist. The live hour should teach the components and rebuild the interesting state transitions, not spend attention on routine scaffolding.</p>
</FeedbackParagraph>

<div class="table-wrap">
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Preseed</th><th>Why it exists before the hour</th><th>Live work still required</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Herdr container</td><td>Pane management and resume should not steal workshop time.</td><td>Use the two panes to observe operator versus loop behavior.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Lakebed list + board shell</td><td>The visual “oh-shit” moment needs to be available early.</td><td>Wire the views to append-only issue events.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Event viewer shell</td><td>The append-only model is a teaching topic, not just storage.</td><td>Show the event that caused each visible move.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Running loop pane</td><td>The daemon should feel alive during the hour.</td><td>Watch automatic pickup while keeping manual operator control.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Pi extension control shell</td><td>The workshop is also about building bespoke harness tools.</td><td>Start, stop, reset, and inspect the loop from the operator pane.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Minimal package guardrails</td><td>Fast checks protect the live build from mush.</td><td>Add only the checks needed for this path.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
</div>

