<span id="hour-beats"></span>

## Lesson states to rebuild run 06

<FeedbackParagraph id="hour-beats" storagePrefix={feedbackStoragePrefix} note="The exact minute marks are less important than protecting the state-machine spine.">
  <p>The hour should feel like prompting the machine into existence on rails. Each move teaches a topic, then proves it in the running surface. If the build slips, cut optional depth, not the tour/vision capture, issue-event contract, reliability check, Lakebed projection, Pi/Herdr control, or first receipt-backed transition.</p>
</FeedbackParagraph>

<div class="table-wrap">
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>State</th><th>Teach</th><th>Visible payoff</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Vision exists</td><td>Before autonomy, tour the rig, run <code>grill-with-docs</code>, and name the repo's boundaries.</td><td><code>VISION.md</code> plus minimal repo setup explain the course.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Reliability floor holds</td><td>Move down for reliability before moving up for leverage.</td><td>First issue events exist; <code>loop check</code> validates them, classifies work, and writes a receipt.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Lakebed projects facts</td><td>Lakebed is the operator/provider surface, not the domain model.</td><td>List, board, and event viewer agree because they project the same events.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Pi controls the loop</td><td>Pi can become the harness around the machine, not just chat.</td><td>Herdr shows operator pane plus loop pane; Pi controls health/status/check-now.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Dispatch is safe</td><td>Claim first, dry-run second, receipt always.</td><td>One ready issue reaches a dispatch receipt without hidden implementation edits.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Maintenance stops visibly</td><td>Agentic maintenance is safe only when bounded by events and stop reasons.</td><td>Gardener proposes/applies bounded events, then stops on duplicate or dirty-state guard.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Specialists are owned</td><td>Multi-agent review is leverage only when roles, artifacts, and stop rules are explicit.</td><td>Scout/reviewer packets produce review artifacts without mutating product state.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Supervisor owns lifecycle</td><td>The top of the leverage arrow is facts, guards, events, and receipts with better lifecycle ownership.</td><td>Shadow XState actor tree agrees with bridge decisions and survives a recovery drill.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
</div>

<span id="happy-path"></span>

## Extreme happy path

<FeedbackParagraph id="happy-path" storagePrefix={feedbackStoragePrefix} note="This is the minimum demo that still feels like the real tool.">
  <p>Tour the prepared rig, run <code>grill-with-docs</code>, capture <code>VISION.md</code>, create the first issue events, run the reliability check, project the same facts into Lakebed, approve one blocked issue, and watch the loop respond through Pi/Herdr control. The loop claims or dry-runs one safe unit of work, writes receipts, proposes a bounded maintenance event, asks a specialist for non-mutating review, and mirrors one decision in a shadow supervisor. Every visible move has an event, receipt, or status line beside it.</p>
</FeedbackParagraph>

<FlowChart
  src="/hour-cut-loop-state.svg"
  title="The one issue state chart"
  caption="The state chart makes the safety story explicit: approval gates the loop, the loop checks projected facts, unsafe work stops, and visible progress always writes a receipt."
  alt="Portrait state chart for a single issue moving from approval required to ready, checking, decision, needs input, in progress, receipt written, and next issue created."
  version="0.6.0"
  wide={true}
/>

## What we intentionally cut

<FeedbackParagraph id="trims" storagePrefix={feedbackStoragePrefix} note="Cutting these is not a value judgment. It is how the hour stays honest.">
  <p>The hour should not productionize every layer. Keep dispatch dry-run, maintenance bounded, specialists non-mutating, and the supervisor in shadow mode. Cut provider swapping, launchd hardening, deep worktree isolation, full subagent orchestration, and long-tail UI polish. The point is to show the seam and the receipt, not finish the platform.</p>
</FeedbackParagraph>

## Source answers from the previous pass

<FeedbackParagraph id="open-questions" storagePrefix={feedbackStoragePrefix} note="These answers are the input that produced the lesson worksheet above.">
  <p>These are no longer open questions. They are the source notes behind the lesson pass: start from a useful preseeded surface, keep the daemon visibly running, make Pi extension control part of the teaching path, preserve list/Kanban/event views in Lakebed, and shape the take-home as a static workshop guide like Matt Pocock's AI Engineer workshop page.</p>
</FeedbackParagraph>

